'''Hay Swamp''' (Hay Swamp Management Area) is a provincially significant [[wetland]] complex, 1839 hectares (4544 acres) in size, located in parts of the central land areas of the municipalities of [[Bluewater, Ontario|Bluewater]] and [[South Huron, Ontario|South Huron]], in [[southwestern Ontario]], [[Canada]]. Approximately {{convert|13|km|mi|sp=us}} in length and {{convert|2|km|mi|sp=us}} in width, at its widest point; it consists of 15 extensively forested individual wetlands, situated on either side, of sections of both the upper drainage of the [[Ausable River (Lake Huron)|Ausable River]] and its tributary, Black Creek.

Hay Swamp is situated at the northern limit of the [[Carolinian forest|Carolinian Biotic Province]] and is categorized as consisting of 98% [[swamp]] and 2% [[marsh]]land. Apart from the Ausable and the Black, its primary source of water is considered to be the local [[Wyoming Moraine]] [[aquifer]]. Hay Swamp is an important regional habitat for wildlife populations including [[white-tailed deer]], [[great blue heron]], ducks, geese, as well as a significant  [[beaver]] presence. The swamp is also home to several plant [[Species at Risk Act|species at risk]], including green dragon and Riddell's goldenrod. Endangered fish and mussel species present in Hay Swamp include, eastern [[Ammocrypta|sand darter]], greenside darter, [[northern riffleshell]], snuffbox, wavy-rayed lampmussel, rainbow mussel and kidneyshell.

Historic logging operations, as well as continuing intensive drainage practices to obtain access to the rich underlying organic [[soil]]s of the swamp, have affected its overall size and health as a [[Habitat (ecology)|natural habitat]]. Since the Ausable River only partially drains the swamp on an ongoing basis, Hay Swamp acts as a natural water 'storage basin', guarding against large-scale [[flood]]ing in other areas downstream and helping to maintain and moderate [[baseflow]] conditions during the summer months. By doing so it improves both the overall [[water quality]] in the Ausable system and aids local fish, bird and wildlife populations during the times of the year when water sources that are available for local wildlife are at a premium. The swamp contains several sites of abandoned 19th and early 20th century farms, including the location of the former community of [[Sodom, Ontario|Sodom]]. Hay Swamp (Hay Swamp Management Area) is administered by the [[Conservation Authority (Canada)|Ausable Bayfield Conservation Authority]].

